summary.seg: This manuscript contains a collection of works by Athanasius, archbishop of Alexandria (295-373 CE). It consists of two parts.

The first and larger part (Part I, f. I, pp. 1-874, and f. [874a]) was copied and signed by the Greek scribe Emmanuel Bembaines, who was active in Venice in the middle of the 16th century. This part of the manuscript was copied from MS Venezia, Biblioteca Nazionale Marciana, gr. 50 (see Savvidis (2010), p. 392), which once belonged to Cardinal Bessarion's collection.

Part II (ff. 875-893, f. [II]) contains three texts by (or attributed to) Athanasius. Two of them are excerpts from texts already present in Part I of the manuscript, the letter to the bishops of Egypt and Libya, and the second letter to Serapion. This part of the manuscript was copied probably in Basel, since its exemplar is MS Basel, Universitätsbibliothek, A.III.4, which by 1515 was in that city ( Opitz (1935), pp. 18, 28).

The manuscript was owned by John Christopherson, master of Trinity College and bishop of Chichester, who acquired it in Italy at great expense: in the preface to the Athanasius' edition printed in 1601 in Heidelberg by Commelinus, it is said, about the manuscript, that Christopherson in Italia magno precio olim coemerat (p. A2v). The codex enjoyed a certain popularity among the first editors of the text: it was used by Petrus Nannius (Pieter Nanninck, 1500-1557) for his Latin translation of Athanasius' works published in Basel by Froben and Episcopius in 1556 (see Provenance), and for the already mentioned edition of the Greek text printed in 1601 in Heidelberg by Commelinus.

Since part II of the manuscript was copied from MS Basil. A.III.4, which was used, along with part I of MS B.9.7, for the Latin translation by Nannius published in 1556 in Basel, one has to wonder, whether this part of the manuscript could have been added to it when it was lent by Christopherson for the 1556 edition. When the manuscript was used for Commelinus' edition, in 1601, part II had already been added to the Trinity manuscript, since the critical notes of this edition cite also the variants from the manuscript (which is indicated as Anglicanus, with the letter "A") for the texts contained in part II: for example, on p. 47 of the notes, the incomplete ending of the last text of part II is mentioned.

supportDesc.foliation: The first leaf of the manuscript is blank and unnumbered (f. [a]). Part I has been paginated in brown ink, in Arabic numerals, in the upper margin right (on the recto of the leaves) and left (on the verso), from 1 to 874; after p. 874 there is a blank unnumbered leaf (f. [874a]). The first leaf of Part I, containing an index, has been foliated I in modern pencil (f. I). Part II exhibits a foliation in brown ink in the upper margin, right, from 875 to 893; the last leaf of the manuscript, blank, is unnumbered (f. [893a]). The leaves are thus numbered as follows: f. [a] + f. I + pp. 1-874, [874a-874b] | ff. 875-893 + f. [II]

condition.p: The manuscript is in good condition. There are (ink?) stains on the leaves throughout, see e.g. p. 320.

binding.p: Western full leather binding over pasteboards. Blind tooled double frame motif on both boards. On the upper, central and lower part of the spine are pasted three paper labels with the shelfmark. 360 250 105
binding.condition: Rebacked. There are scraps on the left cover.

provenance.p: The manuscript was owned by John Christopherson (d. 1558) Christopherson, John, -1558 , Master of Trinity College (1553–1558). On f. [a] recto there is an ownership note, stating also that Christopherson had lent the manuscript to the Basel printers Froben and Episcopius: Est D. Ioannis Christofersoni Angli, Frobenio et Episcopio ab ipso crediti. The edition of Froben and Episcopius, printed in 1556 in Basel, is a Latin translation of Athanasius' works by Petrus Nannius (Pieter Nanninck, 1500-1557); the loan of a manuscript from Christopherson is acknowledged in the prefatory dedication ( Athanasii Magni Alexandrini episcopi, graviss. scriptoris, et sanctiss. martyris, Opera, in quatuor Tomos distributa: quorum tres sunt a Petro Nannio Alcmariano, ad Graecorum exemplarium fidem iam primum conversi, exceptis paucis antehac imperfectis ab eo denuo plenius et Latinius redditis: Quartus, Latina multorum interpretatione fere totus seorsum emissus, nunc in unum digestus et concinnatus [...], Basel 1556.).

history.acquisition: It is not known when precisely the manuscript entered the collection of Trinity College Library. In his will of 1556 John Christopherson bequeathed his books to the library; he died in 1558, but his will was not proved until 1563 (see Gaskell (1980), p. 47). The manuscript arrived in the Library after that date and before 1601, when the edition of Athanasius' works by Commelinus was printed (Heidelberg, 1601), in which the manuscript was used and cited as a codex collegii S. Trinitatis Cantabrigiensi, olim D. Joannis Christophorsoni (the introduction to Commelin's edition can be read also in PG 25, XLIII D l. 7-11). On f. I recto, p. 874, f. 892v and f. 893r there are stamps of Trinity College Library.

recordHist.source: Description (2020) partly draws on M. R. James, The Western Manuscripts in the Library of Trinity College Cambridge (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 1900), vol. 1, pp. 268-270.

support.material:
f. I, pp. 1-874, f. [874a] Western paper, folded in folio. Watermarks: ff. [a], I, pp. 1-49, 217-236, 257-296, 299-314, 345-348, 365-368, 425-428, 437-796. 797-798/815-816, 823-830, 837-874, f. [874a] Assembled letters
P 3 surmounted by a clover ( 32 25 ) in the centre of the leaf, comparable to Sosower Lettres assemblées 34 , which is dated to ca. 1545.
pp. 57-216, 237-256, 297-298/315-316, 317-344, 349-364, 369-424, 429-436, 799-814, 817-822, 831-836 Lion with countermark 3 d/o ( ca. 63 50 ) in the centre of the leaf, comparable to Sosower Lion 4 , which is dated to ca. 1555-1556.

collation.catchwords: Vertical catchwords by the scribe, written from top down, in the lower margin of the last verso of the quires, written in the gutter, not always visible due to a very tight sewing of the quires and to trimming (see e.g. p. 16).
collation.signatures: One signature is visible on p. 417, [κ]β΄ ([2]2); the others have been lost to trimming.

layoutDesc.layout: pp. 1-874: One single column of 30 lines. 250 135

handNote.p: ff. I recto-I verso, pp. 1-874 Hand A: the texts in this part of the manuscript have been written by Emmanuel Bembaines (active mid-16th century) Emmanuel Bembaines (active mid-16th century) who signed his work on p. 874 ( Ἐμμανουὴλ Βεμβαινῆς, RGK I, 113; on him see also RGK II 145; RGK III, 188).
The text is written in brown ink; titles and initials, as well as some marginal notes, in red.
The scribe wrote annotations in the margins and revised the text.

handDesc.handNote: Hand a: a later hand added 7 lines at the end of the Index by Bembaines, on f. I verso, adding to it the texts contained in part II of the manuscript, and the number of page near each item.
Hand b: Passim there are marginal annotations in Greek and in Latin by a contemporary or slightly later hand, see e.g. pp. 67, 194, 418

decoDesc.decoNote:
Several friezes in red ink are present throughout the manuscript at the beginning of the texts:
f. I recto, pp. 137, 419, 448, 624: rope motif
p. 1: chain motif with palmettes
pp. 67, 144, 179, 183, 185, 194, 204, 249, 304, 313, 317, 350, 374, 525, 724, 778: simple undulated linear frieze with clovers at both ends
p. 157: simple undulating frieze with small leaves
pp. 184, 260, 704, 755, 811: repeating pattern of two horizontal strokes, two commas
p. 224: frieze with vegetal motifs in volutes
p. 721: small frieze formed by a series of commas
in some cases, as e.g.on p. 315, titles are preceded by ornamental elements like knots, traced in red ink
Initials with decoration in a branch motif (see e.g. p. 1), or a more simple vegetal decoration (see e.g. p. 67).
Thick minor initials in red ink, see e.g. f. I recto.

The text often ends in a cul-de-lampe disposition. The lines are preceded and followed by three points in red ink (see e.g. p. 312) or contoured by a line in red ink (see e.g. p. 248), which can be decorated with vegeral motifs (see p. 524).

additions.p: On pp. 194 and 721 there are two annotations by later hands citing a Basel manuscript. They probably are to be linked to the preparatory work of the Basel 1556 edition, for which the manuscript was lent (see Provenance). The MS Basiliensis is probably to be identified with Basel, Universitätsbibliothek, A.III.4, which was used as well for that edition ( Opitz 1935, pp. 17-18).
Some marginal annotations in Latin are present also on p. 387.

history.origin:
This part of the manuscript was copied by Emmanuel Bembaines around the
mid-16th century, in all probability in Venice, where the scribe was active and which was the location of the exemplar used by the scribe, MS Marc. gr. 50 ( Savvidis (2010), p. 392), which was part of Cardinal Bessarion's collection (see Opitz (1935), pp. 17-18).

support.material: ff. 882-893, [II] Western paper, folded in folio. Watermarks: Shield with letters/monogram (?) on it, difficult to discern ( 20 15 ) in the centre of the leaf, no precise parallels were found in the main repertoires, comparable small shields with letters/monograms, such as for example Briquet Lettres 9908-9910, are dated in the 16th c. (1530-1570).

collation.p: Part II consists of two quaternions and a binion (the collation has been reconstructed on the basis of the position of the watermark).

layoutDesc.layout: ff. 875r-893r: A single column of 35 to 44 lines. ca. 300-315 ca. 260

handNote.p: ff. 875r-892r l. 8 Hand B: the majority of the texts in part II of the manuscript have been written in a minuscule script datable to the 2nd half of the 16th c. Some forms, as majuscule mu, tau, epsilon, round sigma, suggest that the script could be attributable to a non-native Greek writer.
The text is written in a light brown ink.
ff. 892r l. 9-893r Hand C: another, contemporary, hand continued the last text of part II. Also in this case the script seems to be attributable to a non-native Greek writer.
The text is written in brown ink.

history.origin: This part of the manuscript was copied probably in the second half of the 16th century, as the watermark suggests, possibly in Basel, since this part of the manuscript was copied from Basel, Universitätsbibliothek, MS A.III.4, which by 1515 was in that city ( Opitz 1935, pp. 18, 28). The dating to the second half of the 16th century is, moreover, suggested also by the fact that, when the manuscript was used for Commelinus' edition, in 1601, part II was already present in the Trinity manuscript, since the critical notes of this edition cite also the variants from the manuscript (which is indicated as Anglicanus, with the letter "A") for the texts contained in part II: for example, on p. 47 of the notes the incomplete ending of the last text of part II is mentioned.
